Ùª­jAttributesÙ¯‚€öpExtended SummaryÙ¯‚‡Ù¹‚Ù§x¶Katz centrality computes the centrality for a node based on the centrality of its neighbors. It is a generalization of the eigenvector centrality. The Katz centrality for node $i$ is€Ù¤x.x_i = \alpha \sum_ { j} A_ { ij} x_j + \beta, Ù¹‚Ù§xHwhere $A$ is the adjacency matrix of graph G with eigenvalues $\lambda$.€Ù¹‚Ù§x9The parameter $\beta$ controls the initial centrality and€Ù¤x)\alpha < \frac { 1} { \lambda_ { \max}}. Ù¹‚Ù§y
Katz centrality computes the relative influence of a node within a network by measuring the number of the immediate neighbors (first degree nodes) and also all other nodes in the network that connect to the node under consideration through these immediate neighbors.€Ù¹‚Ù§ylExtra weight can be provided to immediate neighbors through the parameter $\beta$.  Connections made with distant neighbors are, however, penalized by an attenuation factor $\alpha$ which should be strictly less than the inverse largest eigenvalue of the adjacency matrix in order for the Katz centrality to be computed correctly. More information is provided in .€ögMethodsÙ¯‚€öeNotesÙ¯‚„Ù¹‚Ù§x#Katz centrality was introduced by .€Ù¹‚…Ù§xVThis algorithm uses a direct linear solver to solve the above equation. The parameter Ù¡ealphaÙ§x€ should be strictly less than the inverse of largest eigenvalue of the adjacency matrix for there to be a solution. You can use Ù¡xmax(nx.adjacency_spectrum(G))Ù§xH to get $\lambda_{\max}$ the largest eigenvalue of the adjacency matrix.€Ù¹‚Ù§xfWhen $\alpha = 1/\lambda_{\max}$ and $\beta=0$, Katz centrality is the same as eigenvector centrality.€Ù¹‚ƒÙ§xFor directed graphs this finds "left" eigenvectors which corresponds to the in-edges in the graph. For out-edges Katz centrality first reverse the graph with Ù¡kG.reverse()Ù§a.€öpOther ParametersÙ¯‚€öjParametersÙ¯‚…Ù°ƒaGegraphÙ¹‚Ù§pA NetworkX graph€Ù°ƒealphaefloatÙ¹‚Ù§rAttenuation factor€Ù°ƒdbetax,scalar or dictionary, optional (default=1.0)Ù¹‚Ù§xrWeight attributed to the immediate neighborhood. If not a scalar the dictionary must have an value for every node.€Ù°ƒjnormalizeddboolÙ¹‚Ù§x'If True normalize the resulting values.€Ù°ƒfweightxNone or string, optionalÙ¹‚Ù§x´If None, all edge weights are considered equal. Otherwise holds the name of the edge attribute used as weight. In this measure the weight is interpreted as the connection strength.€öfRaisesÙ¯‚Ù°ƒ`mNetworkXErrorÙ¹‚ƒÙ§qIf